Rakuen is a city south of Midgaard, beyond the Eccentric Woodland, founded as a deliberate civilizational counter-argument to Midgaard's registry culture. The Southward Compact — founded by Verath Solen's coalition with conditional backing from Midgaard temple orders and a caravan house — established: common granary duty, public mediation before private reprisal, rotating civic stewardship, strict constraints on hereditary emergency office, and open accounting of food, water, and labor. Haven-Architect Elys Savan designed it around common orchards, cooperative waterworks, and forest integration. Its defining paradox: founded to escape Midgaard's bureaucratic machinery, Rakuen spent two centuries begging to be absorbed by it. Three annexation petitions, three refusals. Southmark Petition refused on ledger-compliance grounds (Rakuen converted its accounting systems; the next refusal had nothing to do with ledger format). Ash Plea refused on route-instability grounds with no commitment to improve the route. Iron Compact Appeal refused eleven years ago on charter-sovereignty grounds. Disaster stacking during the Ash-and-Iron Decades — ashfall, redwater floods, orchard blight, route predation — forced Rakuen to adopt emergency institutions it once condemned: ration towers, salvage courts, labor drafts, escorted convoy mandates. Modern Rakuen is politically divided among the Amendment Track (fourth petition with Kiess certification), Quiet Separatists (maritime independence through Mafdet), and Preservation Coalition (status quo). The Garden Ledger Clerks and Bloom Council are in ongoing tension over the Paradise Thesis text (Bloom Council holds what it claims is authoritative; Clerks maintain an earlier draft with critical Midgaard passages intact; Canopy Compacts believe the full text is at Kiess).

