Rakuen's Kel'Shadra witnessing office during the Violet Compact era was the mechanism through which Midgaard's Sealed Names apparatus was extended to the southern frontier. Persons resettled south under administrative protection codes could formally register testimonies through the Kel'Shadra office — a process that appeared to be testimony preservation but functioned as testimony suppression, routing registered claims to classification levels beyond practical access: "below bell-line; no civic remainder." In Khenari descent accounting, these are testimonies that exist in the system but cannot be reached — present without accessible location, documented without recoverable substance. The office closed at the end of the Violet Compact era without explanation. Its records are somewhere in the Kel'Shadra crypt apparatus. Several of those records concern Rakuen arrivals with inconvenient things to say about who ordered their resettlement and why. The Bloom Council accepted the witnessing office arrangement without fully understanding or choosing to investigate its classification procedures — a failure that Khenari observers read as either ignorance or deliberate non-inquiry, both producing the same outcome. Sacred records require confirmed descent chains. The Kel'Shadra office provided the form of testimony preservation while systematically severing the descent chains that would make the preserved testimonies retrievable. It is, in Khenari terms, a factory for spiritual gaps.

