The three Rakuen annexation refusals can be measured against stated justifications and observable outcomes. Southmark Petition refused on ledger-compliance grounds: Rakuen spent years reformatting its Garden Ledger to Midgaard-compatible registry formats. The Ash Plea refusal had nothing to do with ledger format — demonstrating that the stated reason was not the operative reason. Ash Plea refused on route-instability grounds through the Eccentric Woodland: Midgaard's refusal included no commitment to route improvement. The joint route-stability commission met four times and produced zero binding agreements. The route instability was not addressed; it was cited as a barrier while no action was taken to remove it. Iron Compact Appeal refused on charter-sovereignty grounds eleven years ago, with a supplementary note suggesting Rakuen amend its own Compact — a path Midgaard neither facilitated nor committed to recognizing. The pattern across three refusals: each refusal cited a different administrative reason; after the stated barrier of the first refusal was addressed (ledger format), the second refusal cited a different barrier; the pattern suggests the stated barriers were not the operative barriers. The Garden Ledger Clerks' analysis reaches this conclusion. The empirical record is: three barriers cited, one barrier addressed, one new barrier substituted, one different new barrier substituted, no annexation. Midgaard's consistent classification of aid as "variance relief" (no binding obligation) rather than "subsidy contract performance" (binding obligation) has been maintained across all three refusal periods.

