Rakuen's position in the five-city network is structurally determined: Midgaard controls the southern gate and registry that validates route-access claims; Woodland cells control interior approaches in practice; Rakuen absorbs whatever arrives downstream with no power to compel upstream actors. This logistical trap was identified by Caitha Dunnmark in Year 34 and has not changed in structure. The Quiet Separatist maritime track through Mafdet is the only proposed route around this trap that does not depend on Midgaard's cooperation. Its viability depends on: whether Rakuen's canopy-botanical trade is commercially significant enough to Mafdet's Ledger Houses to justify the administrative investment, whether the Red Sand Accounts' debt-leverage risk can be managed, whether the Reach Wardens and Sand-Sea Carters' Guild would apply Strandline Compact "harbor first" mechanisms to block access, and whether the mercy-freight classification would extend to a non-disaster commercial route. Each dependency links to other network actors. The Garden Ledger Clerks' triangular evidence structure connecting Midgaard, Kowloon, and Rakuen through the Conclave guilt chain is also a network connection — the same three nodes that form the trade subsidy dependency form the three documented points of the Conclave transfer chain. The institutional architecture of the dependency relationship and the institutional architecture of the guilt chain are coterminous. The cities that bear the most responsibility for Rakuen's current condition are the same cities whose grain and registry support Rakuen cannot survive without.
